{"ts":"2026-06-26T22:24:34.931Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing Spatial Visualizations**\n\nI'm now deep-diving into spatial visualization options. The current linear layout is clearly insufficient when the underlying topology is changed. I see a chance to make it feel extremely premium by implementing actual SVG-based spatial layouts that correspond to the topology pattern. This can include a central orchestrator with branches for hierarchical structures, or a star pattern. A swarm topology might show nodes in a mesh-like arrangement with crisscrossing paths. Finally, a DAG topology can be implemented as a branching structure.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T22:24:36.483Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Enhancing the DAG's Visualization**\n\nI'm now very focused on the DAG's visual presentation and how to make it feel expensive. Currently, it's just a stack of cards, but I see immense potential to elevate it. I have to add dynamic node positioning based on selected topology patterns, as well as a canvas grid. To make the premium feel, I'm thinking of adding interactive panning and dragging. But I really think a smooth, bezier curve SVG overlay would be high-end.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T22:24:38.094Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing SVG-Based Connections**\n\nI'm now investigating how to visually connect the nodes. I can use SVG elements between the nodes in absolute positions to render complex topological patterns. I'm thinking of using CSS grid or flexbox for the visual layout, then drawing the SVGs as a separate layer. For instance, the sequential pattern can use glowing dashed SVG pipes, a hierarchical pattern can use SVG lines descending from a supervisor, and a swarm pattern can use glowing criss-crossing lines.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T22:24:40.716Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Visualizing Data Flows**\n\nI'm now focusing on how to represent parallel tracks, with branching and merging SVG lines, on the canvas. I'm visualizing the concept as an interactive, multi-topology cryptographic CAD. The interactive nodes will feature live telemetry simulations, where glowing pulses travel along custom SVG paths that change with the selected routing. It will integrate flawlessly with our design system, incorporating the dark theme, premium styling, and security cues. I'm focusing on the implementation details, like the stages stored in state.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T22:24:42.354Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Mapping Layouts to Patterns**\n\nI'm now figuring out the best ways to visualize different workflow patterns using custom layouts. I'm focusing on a `renderCanvasTopology()` function to lay out the nodes. The structure of the `stages` data structure will be crucial here. For sequential flows, a horizontal chain will be used.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-26T22:24:44.186Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Designing Hierarchical Visuals**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the hierarchical layout. The \"Supervisor\" node will be visually distinct, possibly with a crown. I'll arrange the rest of the nodes below it, with curved SVG paths connecting them. The simulation will feature signals flowing down from the supervisor. The next step will be working on how to arrange the nodes in a horizontal row.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
